<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / International Company News: Earnings at Goodyear climb 30%
in quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Strong operating margins enabled Goodyear, the last of the big US-owned tyre
groups, to lift net income by nearly 30 per cent in the fourth quarter,
despite a slight decline in sales.
The company posted earnings of Dollars 113.2m, or 76 cents a share, in the
final three months of 1993, against Dollars 87.5m, or 61 cents, in the
corresponding period of 1992.
Revenues slipped from Dollars 2.92bn to Dollars 2.91bn, largely because of 6
per cent slide in Europe, where the car industry is severely depressed.
Latin America, with sales 5 per cent higher and operating income up 74 per
cent, continued to outperform other regions. Sales were flat in the US,
despite a strong performance by the domestic car industry.
The announcement was greeted warmly on Wall Street, even though the company
had given investors an accurate estimate of its results two weeks ago. The
stock added Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 49 in early trading, amid expectations
that the company's performance would improve as the US economy expands in
1994.
For the full year, net earnings, excluding extraordinary items and the
effect of accounting changes, improved 33 per cent to Dollars 488.7m, or
Dollars 2.57. Worldwide sales dipped to Dollars 11.64bn, compared with
Dollars 11.78bn, but the year-earlier figure included Dollars 43m in
revenues from businesses which were later discontinued.
</TEXT>
