<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / International Company News: KPMG terminates Spectrum role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Spectrum Information Technologies, the company that Mr John Sculley abruptly
left earlier this week, said yesterday that its accounting firm, KPMG Peat
Marwick, had terminated its relationship with the company.
KPMG was brought in at Spectrum in November by Mr Sculley, the former
chairman and chief executive of Apple Computer. On Monday Spectrum restated
its earnings, based on KPMG's recommendations, to defer Dollars 6.4m in
revenues previously recorded in the past two quarters.
Spectrum said that the accounting firm gave no reason for ending the
relationship, but indicated that the resignation was 'not based on any
accounting disagreements with the company'.
'We view their action as arbitrary and unprofessional,' said Mr Salvatore
Marino, chief financial officer. 'The accounting firm had not yet reviewed
the financial records of the company. We think it is more than coincidental
that their resignation follows that of John Sculley.'
</TEXT>
