<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / International Company News: Viacom tops the Paramount bill -
A look at the final offers for the entertainment group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Dollars 10bn, five-month takeover battle for entertainment group
Paramount Communications may be within days of a final showdown, with cable
company Viacom holding an apparent lead but television shopping channel QVC
Network still fighting hard to win investor support.
Shareholders have until midnight, New York time, on Monday to decide between
the bidders' final offers, and victory will go to whichever company wins
over 50 per cent of Paramount's stock. However, if neither side gets over
half the shares, the battle will continue and the bidders will be free to
alter their terms again.
During the final few days of the campaign, both Mr Sumner Redstone, chairman
of Viacom, and Mr Barry Diller, the film industry executive who heads QVC,
have been wooing the big institutional investors and Wall Street traders who
control much of Paramount's stock in a succession of face to face meetings.
Two issues dominate these sessions: the relative value of the offers, and
which bidder will be better able to exploit the assets of Paramount, which
include Hollywood film studios, book publishing, theme parks and New York's
Madison Square Garden sports arena.
A significant number of investors have already made clear that they intend
to tender their shares to Viacom unless QVC can improve its terms, which the
rules of the Paramount auction forbid it from doing before Monday's close.
Viacom is offering Dollars 107 a share in cash for 50.1 per cent of
Paramount's stock, compared to QVC's Dollars 104 a share. The package of
common stock and other securities QVC is offering for the remaining 49.9 per
cent has a higher theoretic market value than that in Viacom's bid, giving
the overall QVC bid a value of around Dollars 86 a share to Viacom's Dollars
81.50.
QVC's apparent lead is due partly to the fact that Viacom's shares have
fallen sharply as it has looked more like the winner, while QVC's shares
have risen. Investors are concerned about the amount of Viacom paper that
will flood the market in the event of victory, as well as the debt the
winner will be taking on.
However, many investors say they prefer the Viacom offer because it
guarantees to pay up to Dollars 12 a share if its stock trades below a
certain level in the year after a Paramount takeover. The QVC bid lacks any
such mechanism and Mr Diller argues that 'there are no safe harbours. There
might appear to be but there really aren't. They are illusions'.
However, QVC has been hinting that its largest backer, the telephone company
BellSouth, might give a degree of share price support by offering to buy a
certain amount of QVC stock at a particular price over a period of years.
But if it did so before Monday night it might be accused of breaking the
auction rules.
As for strategic fit between the two companies, shareholders are essentially
being presented with a choice between Viacom's depth of management and broad
range of businesses, and Mr Diller's individual proven flair for turning
around troubled Hollywood studios.
Paramount Pictures, the crown jewel among Paramount's assets and the reason
the takeover battle has been fought so long and hard, has a distinctly
lacklustre track record - a fact underlined last week when the group warned
it would suffer a loss of Dollars 35m to Dollars 40m in its third quarter.
Mr Diller, who headed Paramount during one of the studio's successful
phases, and then went on to launch Mr Rupert Murdoch's Fox business as a
fourth television network, says the group's film and television operations
need most work. 'And I've the most experience in those areas . . . that's
not the experience the other side has. It will take them longer.'
Viacom - which bought many of its creative businesses, rather than building
them from scratch - argues that it is the better bet because a merger with
Paramount, together with its simultaneous Dollars 8bn bid for Blockbuster
Entertainment, the video rental retailer, will create a 'global
entertainment powerhouse'.
Viacom says it will bring to the partnership much more depth of management,
its own successful track record in television programming and Blockbuster's
strong cash flow and film and record retailing chain. The combination will
offer new distribution channels for Paramount's studios.
Wall Street was initially unenthusiastic about a
Viacom-Blockbuster-Paramount deal, largely on the grounds that Blockbuster's
video rental business is going to be made obsolete by inter-active,
video-on-demand in the home.
But some analysts have since warmed to the combination. Says Mr Christopher
Dixon of Paine Webber: 'The ability to create efficiencies, cross promote
and develop new businesses holds enormous promise.'
The idea of Mr Diller reviving Paramount still excites Wall Street, which
for the most part believes both bidders would be worthy winners. But with
the strategic arguments finely balanced, perceptions of short-term
shareholder value will win the day, and right now that looks like handing
victory to Viacom.
</TEXT>
<XX>
