<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / International Company News: Total steady in spite of oil
price write-down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Total, the French oil group, yesterday announced estimated net profits of
FFr2.9bn (Dollars 492m) for last year, a slight increase over the FFr2.8bn
in 1992. The result was largely in line with expectations.
Mr Serge Tchuruk, group chairman, said the results demonstrated Total's
resilience to recession in Europe, and the sharp fall in the oil price in
1993. The latest results included an exceptional inventory write-down of
FFr800m relating to the decline in crude oil prices.
Excluding the inventory loss, operating income rose from FFr7.3bn to
FFr7.6bn, while cashflow surged to FFr11.3bn from FFr10bn. Sales remained
stable at about FFr136bn. The effects of a capital increase in April last
year, however, prompted a fall in earnings per share, from FFr13.8 to
FFr13.2.
In spite of the depressed market conditions, Total said it had managed to
pursue its strategy of increasing reserves and production, developing gas
activities, restructuring specialty chemicals activities and extending the
geographical base.
Mr Tchuruk mentioned several areas where the group was expanding its
development and production of oil and gas. Total's projects in Indonesia and
Colombia, for example, should help achieve the company's target - outside
the Middle East - of a 40 per cent increase in production during this year
and next.
In 1993, the group's exploration and production division, which excludes the
Middle East, saw operating profits fall from FFr2.9bn to FFr2.2bn. The
decline was largely blamed on the downturn in the oil price, which averaged
Dollars 17 per barrel of Brent crude, compared with Dollars 19.30 in 1992.
The trading and Middle East division increased its profits in 1993, from
FFr600m to FFr700m, reflecting the low exposure of upstream margins to
declining crude prices, and an improvement in trading and shipping
activities. Including the Middle East, the group's total oil and gas
reserves rose from 3.95m barrels of oil equivalent to 4.07m barrels by the
end of last year.
Operating profits in the refining and marketing division rose sharply from
FFr2.1bn to FFr3.3bn, the result of a slight recovery in refining margins
and a strong improvement in Total's US operations.
In chemicals, however, profits declined by 18 per cent to FFr1.4bn. Total
said the fall reflected the impact of recession in Europe and, in
particular, the weak demand from the automotive industry for its coatings
and paint products.
During the year, gross capital expenditures rose from FFr14.8bn in 1992 to
FFr17.6bn, while the debt-to-equity ratio declined.
</TEXT>
