<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Receivers called in at FMT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FMT Holdings, the former Vickers subsidiary which is viewed as one of the
last global competitors in the British-owned machine tool industry, has
called in the receivers.
Ernst &amp; Young, the accountancy firm, was this week appointed receiver at the
Brighton-based company, whose chairman, Mr Mike Bright, is one of the the
best-known figures in the industry.
News of the receivership was immediately described by observers as a
'disaster' for the industry. However, the company is continuing trading, and
it is understood that the receivers will try to sell it as an ongoing
business.
FMT is one of the few British producers to compete head-on with the much
larger Japanese and German machine tool builders in high-technology
machining centres, linked together by computer control to create flexible
manufacturing systems.
The timing of the receivership was a shock to the industry - many UK
producers have recently been expressing cautious optimism after three years
of recession.
FMT even held an open day last week to display new products, and according
to one observer, appeared to be relatively busy.
However, it is believed that the company has been short of new orders and
has also been hit by price-cutting in the UK market by German and Japanese
companies.
It is understood that the receivers have already made about 30 redundancies
from a workforce of 160.
The receivership is a further twist in the chequered history of a company
that, as Kearney, Trecker and Marwin, once employed 2,000 people with
several factories in Sussex.
In the 1970s, as KTM, it became a subsidiary of Vickers, but in 1988 Mr
Bright and five senior managers bought it from the luxury cars and
engineering group in a Pounds 10.6m buy-out.
</TEXT>
