<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Owners Abroad hit by Pounds 12m exceptional
costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Owners Abroad yesterday announced profits before tax and exceptional items
of Pounds 17.8m for the 12 months to October 31, compared with Pounds 30.4m
the previous year.
Mr Francis Baron, chief executive, said Pounds 12m of exceptional items had
pulled the pre-tax profits figure down to Pounds 5.8m (Pounds 25.5m).
Mr Baron said Pounds 4.9m of the exceptional costs were attributable to the
successful defence last year to a takeover bid by Airtours, its rival, the
establishment of its strategic alliance with travel agents Thomas Cook and
other professional fees.
A further Pounds 1.5m of exceptional costs arose from compensation paid to
former directors of the group. Mr Howard Klein, chairman, Mr Roger Allard,
managing director, and Mr Geoffrey Stone, finance director, resigned last
year.
Mr Baron would not say how the compensation was divided between the three.
The remaining costs related to property provisions in the UK and Spain.
Turnover fell 8 per cent to Pounds 710m as a result of holiday price
discounting and reduced airline revenues.
Cash balances at the year-end were Pounds 100.3m, compared with Pounds
98.4m.
COMMENT
The City was cheered yesterday by the absence of any previously undisclosed
bad news. Mr Baron is also widely seen to be taking appropriate action to
restructure the group. A cause for concern, however, is how Thomson and
Airtours, the group's larger competitors, plan to respond to Owners Abroad's
new management. Mr Baron said Lunn Poly and Going Places, the larger groups'
travel agents chains, had damaged Owners Abroad last year by pushing Thomson
and Airtours holidays. Owners Abroad's link with Thomas Cook gives it some
advantages but does not allow it to respond fully in kind. Expected 1994
profits of Pounds 21m and earnings of 7.4p put the group on a prospective
multiple of 16, which is probably generous. Most analysts, however, do not
expect restructuring benefits to show through until 1995, when expected
Pounds 27.5m profits and earnings of 9.7p provide a more realistic multiple
of 12.
</TEXT>
