<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Leading Article: Anti-dumping
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Having congratulated itself on the outcome of the Uruguay Round trade
negotiations, the European Union now seems bent on thwarting by the back
door the liberalisation it is intended to promote. That door has been opened
by the decision of the Council of Ministers this week to make anti-dumping
duties subject to approval by a simple majority of member states, instead of
by a qualified majority vote.
The change threatens to make it even easier for the EU to wield a
protectionist weapon which it has deployed with frequency in the past
decade. All the more so since Brussels plans to double its anti-dumping
staff and speed up the handling of cases.
Recent history does not inspire confidence that the new powers will be
exercised wisely. Brussels' anti-dumping procedures are so obscure,
arbitrary and elastic that they can be used to find that almost any third
country exporter is guilty of 'unfair' price competition and punished
accordingly. The result is huge costs to EU consumers - Pounds 1.3bn
annually for consumer electronics products alone, according to Britain's
National Consumer Council.
The change in voting rules is unlikely to be revoked, since it was an
explicit condition of France's acceptance of the Uruguay Round package. In
the short term, the best hope that it will not be abused is that Sir Leon
Brittan, the liberal-minded trade commissioner, will exercise restraint in
proposing anti-dumping actions. However, he may not remain in his job after
this year. Much stronger institutional safeguards and greater transparency
are needed.
Brussels has gone some way by separating investigations of alleged dumping
and injury, providing more information to consumers and allowing for
speedier judicial review. It needs to go further. Management of the
anti-dumping division needs to be tightened. In addition, all proposed
actions should be analysed by the Commission's economic and competition
directorates. These analyses should be published, along with the division's
own arguments and calculations.
Such measures would not guarantee fairness and impartiality. But they should
enable consumers, both businesses and individuals, to gauge the price they
were being asked to pay - and require governments to justify it publicly.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
</DOC>
