FT  10 FEB 94 / Observer: From Gotcha to Gandhi
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
He's taken tea with the Indian president; conversed with finance minister
Manmohan Singh; brought chaos to Delhi's jammed roads; and posed for several
front-page photos with his wife. Who he? Why, Rupert Murdoch, of course.
What brings him to town? Satellite TV seems to be the answer; with China out
of bounds, India is his Star TV's biggest market. A 10-day visit has seen
him glad-hand a host of India's top movers and shakers.
It may be a private trip, but the Aussie-born media mogul has overshadowed
the state visit of Czech president Vaclav Havel, in India to get the Indira
Gandhi Award for Peace, Development and Disarmament. Havel is a head of
state, but the local media is keener on featuring the man who gave the world
such classic newspaper headlines as 'Up yours, Delors'.
Still not everyone was taken in. One paper wrote 'Murdoch probably needs
India more than India needs Murdoch'. The length of his stay suggests there
may be some truth in this verdict.
</TEXT>
