<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Hard core or soft centre: A look at the role of extensive
cross-shareholdings in French industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Like a spider spinning an intricate web, France's privatisation programme is
forging a series of links between some of the country's most powerful
financial and industrial companies. The group of long-term shareholders in
Elf Aquitaine, the oil company in the final stages of privatisation, is a
case in point. Union des Assurances de Paris, France's biggest insurer,
Banque Nationale de Paris, one of the biggest banks, and Renault, the car
group, are among those that will hold a combined 10 per cent of the oil
group's shares and form a core of stable investors, dubbed a noyau dur.
Elf should return the favour in several state sell-offs. It has already
stumped up almost FFr1bn (Pounds 110m) to become part of the noyau dur of
BNP. Renault and UAP are also likely to find the oil group near the top of
their share registers when they step up to the auction block later this
year.
Cross-shareholdings and noyaux durs are already common between French
financial and industrial groups. But the government's plan to privatise 21
of the country's largest companies, with a market value of more than
FFr300bn, creates the potential for a substantial expansion of the system.
In so doing, it raises several important questions, from the motives behind
the expanding web of cross-shareholdings, to its strength and efficiency.
The answers will help determine how French capitalism evolves from its
current position between the German and Japanese models - of substantial
equity and management links between industry, banks and insurance companies
 -and the liberal, market-based model of Anglo-Saxon economies.
There is a broad agreement on the reasons behind the rise of the noyaux durs
and their role in the current round of privatisations. 'The system is
designed to provide a minimum of stability and protection for companies
moving into the private sector,' says Mr Jean-Rene Fourtou, chairman of
Rhone Poulenc, the chemicals and pharmaceuticals group, which was privatised
at the end of last year.
In the absence of powerful institutional investors, the duty falls to banks,
insurance companies and industrial groups. 'We have no heavy investors, such
as pension funds,' says Mr Elie Cohen, head of research at CNRS, the
economic and social research centre in Paris. 'So we had to invent
something, and we invented cross-shareholdings. It is the problem of
developing capitalism without capital.' The weakness of pension funds is a
result of France's concentration on pay-as-you-earn contributions that
provide benefits for retired employees.
There is less agreement, however, on the merits of the noyau dur system.
'This kind of set-up grates with some international investors,' says one US
fund manager. 'By reducing the discipline of the market, and maybe the
threat of takeover, it raises the risk of inefficiencies creeping into a
company.' Such concerns, however, have not prevented US investors
participating strongly in the three privatisations undertaken so far.
Mr Francois Morin, director of Lerep, the economic and industrial research
centre, criticises the blurred responsibility of company directors. 'Is
their responsibility to their partners in their cross-shareholdings or to
all shareholders?' he asks. For Mr Cohen, there is the additional problem of
the efficiency of the allocation of financial resources. 'It is clearly not
the best system for an industrial company like Rhone Poulenc or St Gobain to
spend scarce capital on buying a stake in a bank,' he says. 'They should be
investing in their core businesses.'
Not surprisingly, the government's political opponents go further. Mr
Laurent Fabius, the former Socialist prime minister, last week attacked what
he described as 'armchair capitalism' in which appointees of the
centre-right government of Mr Edouard Balladur, such as Mr Jacques
Friedmann, chairman of UAP, were forming a club of financial and industrial
companies.
'The heads of the companies being privatised are each on the boards of the
other, they exchange capital and are all close to the prime minister,' said
Mr Fabius. 'This poses a problem to the development of French industry.'
Industrialists accept that there are drawbacks to the system, including the
diversion of capital from their core activities. But they argue that the
powers of the noyaux durs are relatively limited, and reject the notion that
cross-shareholdings create inefficiencies by providing protection. 'What
would be the reaction of my so-called friends if they were offered four
times the market price for Rhone Poulenc shares?' asks Mr Fourtou,
rhetorically. 'A group of core shareholders is no guarantee of security,'
says Mr Marc Vienot, chairman of Societe Generale, one of France's largest
banks.
For Mr Vienot and many others within the world of French finance and
industry, the power and the permanence of the noyau dur and the pattern of
cross-shareholdings is overstated. 'Our core shareholders do not play a
significant role in the strategy of the group. They regard it as more of a
financial investment and I would expect some of them to leave or reduce
their shareholdings over the next few years,' says one chief executive.
In the case of privatisation issues, core investors are usually subject to a
commitment to hold the majority of their shares for a set period, often
about 18 months. Within that period they can sell shares to other core
investors who also retain a pre-emption right on noyau dur share sales for
the next few years. 'It is not a very serious or permanent constraint in the
grand order of things,' says one French merchant banker, who adds that the
large number of core investors, and the relatively small level of their
stakes, limits their influence.
There are advocates of a shift towards a German-style system of more
powerful ties between banks and industrial companies cemented by substantial
shareholdings. Mr Michel Albert, for example, former chairman of the AGF
insurance group and now a member of the Bank of France monetary policy
committee, argues such a system allows companies to develop long-term
strategies, secure from the short-term pressures of the market.
There are also practical examples. Credit Lyonnais took stakes of between 10
per cent and 20 per cent in a number of groups including Pinault-Printemps,
the retail company, and Usinor-Sacilor, the steel group. 'Credit Lyonnais
under Jean Yves Haberer (its chairman until last December) was trying to be
a sort of French Deutsche Bank,' says Mr Cohen.
Few other banks have sought to copy its strategy. Instead, many
industrialists see an evolution, albeit gradual, towards a more Anglo-Saxon
model. 'It is true that the lack of big institutional investors has pushed
the system towards one of cross-participations between the main industrial
and financial actors as in Japan or Germany,' says Mr Fourtou of Rhone
Poulenc. 'But I don't see it as a permanent arrangement because French
industrial solidarity is not so strong.'
'My desire is that the system of noyau dur is a system of transition and
that we move towards the Anglo-Saxon model,' says Mr Vienot of Societe
Generale. The German system has its weaknesses, he says, pointing to last
month's near-collapse of Metallgesellschaft, the metals group, despite the
presence of several of Germany's biggest banks and financial companies on
its board.
Whether Mr Vienot's desire is satisfied will depend in particular on the
development of French pension funds and the expansion of long-term savings.
Both processes are under way. Faced with a state pension system with a
deficit of almost FFr20bn and approaching breaking point, Mr Edmond
Alphandery, the economy minister, is preparing a draft bill on pension
reform to be presented to parliament this spring. Tax incentives for money
market savings funds have already been reduced in favour of longer-term
deposits.
Creating pension funds will, however, take time. 'It will happen, but not
overnight,' says Mr Didier Cherpitel, managing director of J. P. Morgan, the
US bank, in Paris. Most industry observers estimate it could take 15 to 20
years to build pension funds capable of playing a substantial role in
industrial investment and able to alleviate the need for
cross-shareholdings.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Elf Aquitaine.
    Union des Assurances de Paris.
    Banque Nationale de Paris.
    Renault.
</CO>
<XX>
