<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Personal View: Why Russia is not a special case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAROLD JAMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the most curious assumptions about developments in Russia is that we
from the outside can somehow steer them in the right direction by an
appropriate choice of actions. It expresses itself in the belief that the
west has more power and influence than do Russians in moulding the Russian
destiny. The search for those outside Russia who might be accountable for
the debacle has been intense, particularly in the wake of the setbacks to
reform caused by the resignations of Mr Yegor Gaidar and Mr Boris Fyodorov.
Some observers blame the undoubtedly careless comment by the US ambassador
at large to the former Soviet Union, Mr Strobe Talbott, last year that there
has been too much shock and too little therapy. This was obviously untrue. A
striking feature about the past two years of Russian policy is how little
shock there has been.
The response of one of the foreign advisers responsible for advising the
Russian Federation to follow the shock course was even more curious. Harvard
economics professor Jeffrey Sachs has repeatedly denounced the international
community - the G7, the World Bank, and, in particular, the International
Monetary Fund - for failing to cushion the shock of the transition to the
market with sufficient support measures. He says international institutions
should have taken a bold gamble and supported with very large transfers of
resources those few people (Mr Sachs's friends) who promised that they could
see how Russia might be changed. According to him, almost every successful
stabilisation effort in the past has relied on generous foreign support.
Mr Sachs's favourite example of a successful foreign-supported stabilisation
is the aftermath of the German hyper-inflation of the early 1920s. It was at
the time often called the 'miracle of the Mark'. A reforming new central
bank president, Mr Hjalmar Schacht, broke with the old conservatives, and
introduced a new and stable currency. A few months after his currency
stabilisation, Germany was supported through a major international loan, the
Dawes Loan ( of 1924); and foreign central banks gave considerable help with
short-term measures to ensure the stability of the new Mark on the foreign
exchanges.
Meanwhile, the government followed an austerity course that was bitterly
unpopular. The only way that it could be sold politically to a sceptical and
disenchanted German electorate was as the inevitable price to be paid for
foreign assistance, and for the prospect of the inflow of foreign credits.
As long as these credits flowed, Germany managed a precarious stability.
Once something went wrong, though, ever larger numbers of people believed
the foreign contribution to the stabilisation to be the source of their
misfortunes. They began to vote in large numbers for the National Socialist
party, and the democratic order collapsed.
Too much effort had been expended on devising complicated schemes to help
Germany and imposing them from the outside, and not enough with building
domestic consensus about reform. One of the perpetual dilemmas of an
operation mounted as an obvious aid mission is that it leads to suspicions
of political manipulation. The realistic way to avoid such suspicions is to
de-politicise assistance as far as possible.
One of the most important conceptual contributions of the Bretton Woods
conference (which created the World Bank and IMF) was the idea of equal and
uniform treatment of all members of a new financial order. It was intended
to avoid the excessive politicisation of 1920s international rescue
operations - all of which failed in the long run. There would be no
'favourites' or 'darlings', but a community of states supporting each other
in times of difficulty through a regulated institutional mechanism.
Such an approach created a series of incentives for compliance, and for
opening to the world economy and for the creation of prosperity, growth and
stability, that were not merely political bribes or hand-outs. It also
emphasised the need for adequate domestic support, and for avoiding the
impression of a course imposed from the outside.
If we put our trust too blindly in a few specific individuals, rather than
in an institutionally anchored and broadly supported reform exercise, we are
almost bound to be disappointed. Perhaps we should remember that Mr Sachs's
favourite architect of the German economic stabilisation of the 1920s, Mr
Schacht, soon became Hitler's minister of economics and the 'wizard' of
National Socialist rearmament.
The author is professor of history at Princeton University, and author of
The German Slump: Politics and Economics 1924-1936 (OUP)
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
