<PROFILE>_AN-EBJCNADQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Leading Article: Mr Hosokawa must say no
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The summit in Washington on Friday between Japan's prime minister, Mr
Morihiro Hosokawa, and US president Bill Clinton is unlikely to be a
success. But this need not be a bad thing. As US negotiators were fond of
saying in the Uruguay Round of trade negotiations, better no agreement than
a bad agreement. If the US were to obtain all it wants, this summit would be
a disaster.
The background to the meeting is long-standing US resentment over the
Japanese trade and current account surpluses and the low penetration of the
Japanese market by imports. To these complaints have been added more
immediate worries about the Japanese economy, stagnant since the fourth
quarter of 1991.
In pressing US concerns on the Japanese authorities, the Clinton
administration has made two innovations: first, it has made the relationship
with Japan among the highest priorities for its foreign policy and, second,
it has demanded Japanese agreement to qualitative and quantitative criteria
for assessing success. So far the Clinton administration's attempt has
failed. Mr Jeffrey Garten, the US commerce undersecretary, has even claimed
that the two sides 'do not seem to have even a common understanding of the
problem, let alone a consensus on the solutions'.
This is not that surprising, since US trade demands represent almost perfect
examples of the mercantilist fallacy. Where the US makes more sense is on
macroeconomic policy. The difficulty here is that, however desirable a
strong recovery in the Japanese economy would be, such things cannot be
secured to order. The Japanese government's announcement this week of
agreement on a Y15,250bn (Pounds 95bn) stimulatory package of tax cuts,
increased spending and loans should help. But the US is entitled to be
cynical about the effectiveness of such packages, since this is already the
fourth one since August 1992. It is questionable, for example, whether
Japanese consumers will start spending in response to a tax reduction in
effect for just one year
If Mr Clinton needs to recognise the limits on what he can hope to obtain
over macroeconomic stimulation, how much more is this true of trade policy?
In the former area at least, he is trying to push the Japanese in the right
direction. In the latter he is doing the opposite.
Why would the quantitative indicators sought by the US be such a dire error?
One reason is that an indicator is bound to become a binding target, as has
been demonstrated only this week by the hostile reaction of US
industrialists to a decline in the foreign share of the Japanese
semiconductor market to 18.1 per cent, less than two percentage points below
the agreed level. How could the reaction be otherwise, when it is suspicion
of Japan that justifies these indicators in the first place? Given the
suspicions, failure to achieve any indicator will be taken as proof not of
the difficulties, but of bad faith.
The very act of acceptance by the Japanese government implies agreement that
it does control industry. But it also represents a commitment to increase
that control. Every failure to achieve a target would then be condemned as
malfeasance and every success as proof that the government does have the
means to deliver on such targets. Either way, the result would be both more
quantitative targets and more rigid administration of existing ones. Since
the European Union and other partners would join in, pretty soon Japan would
be as cartelised as its critics already say it is. What is more, these
demands will inevitably spread to other bilateral trade relationships.
Mr Hosokawa must say no, because the alternative would be dreadful. Saying
no could well have horrible consequences too, particularly if Mr Clinton
cannot be persuaded to take on the Japan-bashers in Congress. The outcome
could even include a spate of Congressionally-mandated actions against
Japan. Japan's only possible response would be to make this debate
multilateral, which is what it should have been all along. However difficult
it may be for Mr Hosokawa, what the world now needs from Japan is
imagination and determination.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MKTS  Foreign trade.
</TP>
