<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Work ailments cost up to Pounds 9bn a year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Accidents and illness at work are costing employers between Pounds 4bn and
Pounds 9bn a year, the equivalent of as much as 10 per cent of all UK
industrial companies' trading profits, the Health and Safety Executive said
yesterday.
In a report based on the most comprehensive research the executive has
undertaken in the field, it calculates that accidents and illness at work
are costing the economy overall between Pounds 11bn and Pounds 16bn a year,
between 2 per cent and 3 per cent of gross domestic product or a year's
economic growth.
The cost to employers, it says, is 30m lost working days, the equivalent of
Pounds 360 for every working man and woman.
In spite of the findings Mr Michael Forsyth, the employment minister, said
yesterday that Britain's health and safety standards were the best in the
world.
'Lots of red tape does not necessarily lead to a healthier and safer
workplace,' he said.
Yet union leaders believe that any de-regulation of health and safety could
prove a false economy.
Mr Frank Davies, chairman of the Health and Safety Commission, which
oversees the executive, said the report proved that accidents hurt
companies' balance sheets. 'I doubt if many managements understand what
accidents actually cost,' he said. Most of the costs tended to be uninsured
and hidden away on profit and loss accounts under production, insurance or
labour costs or as write-offs.
The report said the cost to employers included compensation to injured
workers, replacing staff involved in an accident and repairing equipment.
The findings were based upon figures in the Department of Employment's 1990
Labour Force Survey and case studies carried out by the executives' accident
prevention advisory unit.
The studies, which looked at non-injury as well as injury accidents and
illnesses, centred upon a construction site, a creamery, a transport haulage
company, a North Sea oil production platform and an National Health Service
hospital.
It found that the construction company lost Pounds 700,000 a year through
accidents and ill health, the creamery almost Pounds 1m, the transport
company Pounds 196,000, the hospital Pounds 400,000 and the oil production
platform Pounds 3.7m.
The report, based on figures from the 1989-1990 financial year, estimated
that illness and injury led to the loss of 30m working days in a single
year. About 1.6m injury accidents in the year had led to absence from work
equivalent to 18m lost working days. Some 5,000 of those injured had to give
up work permanently.
The commission believes that as much as 70 per cent of the cost of accidents
and ill health could be prevented by management.
A group of Nottinghamshire Labour MPs are meeting with Mr Forsyth today in
an attempt to have a public inquiry into the Bilsthorpe colliery accident
that resulted in the deaths of three miners in August. The report of the
Health and Safety Executive investigation into the accident is to be
published today.
Costs to the British Economy of Work Accidents. HSE Books, PO Box 1999,
Sudbury, Suffolk CO10 6FS. Pounds 13.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6321 Accident and Health Insurance.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
    P1222 Bituminous Coal-Underground.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
