<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Germans fail to bid for Swans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The board of German shipbuilder Bremer Vulkan, which had expressed interest
in the troubled Swan Hunter shipyard, has decided not to bid. The decision
came after the company failed to find a partner for the venture.
GEC, which is also believed to be a potential bidder for Swans, declined
yesterday to reveal its intentions. The prospects of Swan Hunter, which has
been in receivership since May, being sold as a shipbuilder now depend
increasingly on whether the UK government is willing to assist a sale.
The only company to confirm that it wishes to place a bid, French
shipbuilder Constructions Mecaniques de Normandie, has suggested that the
government-funded Tyne and Wear Development Corporation buy Swan Hunter's
main Tyneside sites and then lease the facilities to CMN.
Such a deal would anger rival UK warship yards, which have already attacked
the recent European Union decision, supported by the UK government, to grant
Swan Hunter limited eligibility to intervention funding subsidy.
Mr Fred Henderson, chairman of UK subsidiary CMN Support Services, said the
idea of CMN leasing Swan Hunter facilities from the development corporation
was not a form of government aid because CMN would pay the market rent for
the land.
It was not out of the question that CMN might buy Swans' site, he said, but
the more capital investment that was required, the more CMN needed to be
confident of workload in the near future.
'We most certainly require a number of assurances and guarantees from the
government on a whole host of matters,' said Mr Henderson. These included
whether a CMN-owned Swans would be competing on an even playing field for
export work.
Mr Alastair Balls, development corporation chief executive, said yesterday
it was awaiting firm figures from CMN following its leasing-deal suggestion.
Mr Steve Byers, Labour MP for Wallsend, said: 'If the government stands to
one side they are basically signing the death certificate.'
</TEXT>
