<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Adverts fall closes engineer magazine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Engineering, a magazine for 'innovators in technology, manufacturing and
management', which was founded in 1866, is closing.
The Design Council, which owns and publishes the magazine, announced
yesterday that the February issue would be the last because of continuing
losses.
The controlled circulation publication, which had an ABC circulation of
23,000 in 1992, was sent mainly to those involved in engineering design and
senior management in relatively smaller companies. It is a sector hit hard
by the recession and the magazine has found it difficult to win enough
advertising to survive.
Mr Anthony Land, publishing director of the Design Council said yesterday:
'I think we have done pretty well in all the circumstances but nevertheless
not well enough.'
In its December editorial the magazine bewailed the position of engineering
in UK society compared with European rivals. It said: 'Until engineering is
seen as both crucial to our economy and indeed spiritually enlightening we
will stay a second rate industrial nation.'
</TEXT>
