<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Tory attacks red-tape bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A former Conservative defence minister yesterday added his voice to
criticism of the government's plans to give itself greater powers to repeal
legislation.
Speaking in the Commons a day after the de-regulation bill gained its second
reading, Sir Michael Neubert, MP for Romford, delivered a strong warning
about the possible consequences of allowing ministers to take too much power
in their drive to cut red tape.
Sir Michael asked MPs: 'Isn't it less than satisfactory that the only
safeguard against ministerial misjudgment in the exercise of delegated
powers of de-regulation is the consideration of 90 minutes for statutory
instruments which are unamendable by this House?'
He also expressed concern that representations made during the period of
consultation promised before changes were made might be ignored.
Replying for the government, Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister,
said that the public would benefit from the removal of 'antique, medieval
restrictions which have no place in the modern age'.
The bill - which was passed with a government majority of 37 - would allow
ministers to repeal primary legislation by statutory order.
A number of Tories said they were likely to vote against the government when
the bill reached committee stage.
</TEXT>
