<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / New ploy by French in quest for jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
French employees will be able to convert money from company profit-sharing
schemes into paid holiday if another government plan designed to reduce the
country's record unemployment wins approval.
The proposed money-for-time exchange is included in an update of the 1966
worker participation law proposed by the French cabinet yesterday. Another
feature of the scheme, yet to be approved by parliament, would allow
employees to take profit shares early provided they spend the money on a car
or home improvements.
The government's use of worker participation legislation not only to promote
industrial democracy but also to encourage consumption and counter
unemployment illustrates its determination to leave no stone unturned in its
quest for jobs.
However, with that interest in worker participation that distinguishes the
Gaullist RPR party from UK conservatives, Mr Edouard Balladur's government
is also proposing to give employees holding more than 5 per cent of their
company's capital (including profit-sharing schemes) the right to call a
general shareholders' meeting to elect worker representatives to the board.
Company chiefs are forecasting that investment will have risen by 3 per cent
in January, reversing a steady fall since 1991, according to a survey by
Insee, the government statistics agency.
</TEXT>
