<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Bonn boosts part-time work: Government bodies are ordered to
change the way they hire staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The German government has ordered government ministries and federal agencies
to offer all their vacancies in future to part-time as well as full-time
workers, as part of a programme to promote part-time employment.
The move was agreed by the cabinet in Bonn yesterday, following publication
of Monday's grim unemployment figures, which topped 4m for the first time in
the history of the federal republic.
Ms Angela Merkel, minister for youth and women's affairs, said federal
agencies had been told to report back on their progress in encouraging
part-time workers, who must be offered the same career prospects as
full-time civil servants.
The government maintains that 2.5m workers, mainly women, would like to work
in part-time jobs. However, currently only 17 per cent of jobs in Germany
are worked part-time, compared with 34 per cent in the Netherlands.
Ms Merkel said that a recent study indicated that at least 1.5m jobs could
be created by work sharing, and that 30 per cent of workers were ready to
work less and earn less.
The latest moves are part of the government's programme of deregulation and
privatisation measures, which amount to the main element in its job-creation
strategy.
Yesterday, Mr Gunter Rexrodt, economics minister, again urged an
acceleration in deregulation and privatisation, measures, he said, which had
enjoyed widespread support at a conference in Bonn on the problem of
Germany's lack of international competitiveness.
He called for privatisation of the savings bank network - a move fiercely
resisted by the banks themselves - as well as the break-up of the monopoly
control of the gas and electricity grids.
The cabinet yesterday approved a new motorway tax for road haulage
operators, who will have to pay up to DM2,500 (Pounds 954) a year for heavy
trucks.
Mr Matthias Wissman, the transport minister, said it was possible a similar
tax would be introduced for passenger cars, but not before the end of the
year.
Germany wants such a measure to be introduced throughout the European Union.
</TEXT>
