<DATE>940210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Oslo expects to meet EU deadline: Norway's new foreign
minister gives optimistic view of entry negotiations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY and KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Norway's new foreign minister, Mr Bjorn Tore Godal, said yesterday that Oslo
could complete its negotiations for entry to the European Union by the
deadline of next month and go on to win approval from the Norwegian
electorate in a referendum in the autumn or early winter.
Mr Godal's assessment, in an interview with the Financial Times, was the
most optimistic to date from a country usually seen as the most difficult
case in the present EU enlargement talks, which also include Austria,
Finland and Sweden.
It came despite what Mr Godal acknowledged were 'disappointing' positions
taken by the EU this week on the issues of regional and agricultural aid and
the prospect of further hard negotiations on fisheries policy. Mr Godal, who
took over as foreign minister last month following the death of Mr Johan
Jorgen Holst, said he did not underestimate the problems but that they could
be overcome given 'a sufficient degree of creativity' from both sides.
'I think we have strong political will in the (EU) council of ministers; we
have strong political will on the part of the applicant governments. There
is a political momentum now in the whole procedure which could favour a
solution to the remaining problems by early March.'
In that case, a referendum was likely in 'autumn or early winter', he said.
He was encouraged by a recent increase in public support for membership. 'It
is modest, but it is followed by an even larger decrease on the No side. So,
with a good negotiated result, and with the likelihood of Swedish and
Finnish entry and the further activation of the political arguments (in
favour) I foresee a Yes majority. It won't be easy, but we are closer to
that than people normally imagine, both in Europe and at home.'
However, Mr Godal, who was previously directly in charge of the EU
negotiations as trade minister, made clear he expected the onus of
compromise needed to conclude an accession agreement to fall on the Union
side.
Norway is demanding that Nordic agriculture be treated permanently as a
special case and wants a transition period for adjustment of its high farm
subsidies to EU levels. It is refusing to allow Union access to its
fisheries beyond quotas already agreed under the European Economic Area
accord and wants to continue to manage independently fish stocks in its
northern-most waters.
But Mr Godal said his country's agriculture and fisheries were 'peanuts in
the broader European context'. Norway would be a net contributor to the EU.
The accession agreement also had to 'pass the test of a referendum' among a
sceptical Norwegian electorate.
'It really depends on the political will and recognition among the Union
members to realise the importance of our positions,' he said.
'Why should they not give a clear signal to their negotiators on agriculture
and fisheries that for foreign policy reasons they have to find solutions to
these problems? . . . to the extent that this will be reflected in the
negotiating positions, we will have a solution.'
</TEXT>
