<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Nato orders Serbian pull-back: Air strikes threatened in 10
days unless Sarajevo artillery is withdrawn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nato last night ordered the Bosnian Serbs to withdraw their artillery
encircling Sarajevo or face air strikes. The alliance ultimatum gave the
Serbs 10 days from midnight tonight to comply.
The dramatic Nato move, its most explicit threat of military intervention in
the 22-month Bosnian war, came a few hours after Bosnian Serb commanders,
under pressure, promised to move their guns from the hills around Sarajevo
and observe a ceasefire in the battered city.
US president Bill Clinton said Nato hoped that Bosnian Serb actions would
make air strikes unnecessary. 'But no one should doubt Nato's resolve,' he
said. 'Nato is now set to act.'
The 16-member Nato alliance decided to create a 20km (12.5 mile) 'exclusion
zone' around Sarajevo. All heavy weapons, including artillery, tanks and
mortars must be moved out of the zone or placed under United Nations
supervision.
Heavy weapons left inside this zone 'will, along with their direct and
essential military support facilities, be subject to Nato air strikes', a
communique warned.
Nato also warned that, even before the deadline, it was ready to unleash air
strikes on heavy weapons found responsible for shelling civilians in
Sarajevo.
The decision is a watershed in the history of the Nato alliance, which is
primed for offensive action for the first time since it was founded in 1949
to hold back communism. It came after more than 12 hours of talks, with
Greece, an ally of Serbia, dissociating itself from the ultimatum without
blocking it.
Mr Manfred Worner, Nato secretary-general, said there was no need to go back
to the UN Security Council for fresh authority to conduct air strikes. He
appealed to Russia to support efforts to persuade the warring Serbs, Moslems
and Croats to reach a political settlement in Bosnia.
Mr Worner said there should be no speculation about the seriousness of the
10-day ultimatum. 'The deadline is firm . . . We are not looking to use
force. We prefer a negotiated solution agreed by all the parties.'
Nato explicitly authorised the commander-in-chief of allied forces in
southern Europe to launch air strikes at the request of the UN.
Air strikes taking place before the expiry of the deadline would need the
approval of Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN secretary-general, Mr Worner said.
After the deadline, attacks could take place simply 'in close co-ordination'
with Mr Boutros Ghali.
The Nato ambassadors hammered out the ultimatum in Brussels amid growing
political pressure in the west for a military response to last Saturday's
shelling of the Sarajevo market, when 68 civilians were killed and more than
200 wounded.
During more than 12 hours of intense debate, Canada voiced concern that an
open threat to intervene for the first time in the Bosnian civil war could
put at risk nearly 200 lightly armed Canadian UN peacekeepers trapped in the
eastern Moslem enclave of Srebrenica.
But the issue was pressed by France, the US and the UK. Britain, a long-time
sceptic on military intervention, supported a Franco-American draft setting
a deadline for a pull-back.
The wider diplomatic goal is to use a withdrawal to demilitarise Sarajevo
and persuade the Bosnian Moslems to agree to a political settlement.
The promise given by Bosnian Serb commanders yesterday was made in an accord
with the Moslem-led Bosnian government army in talks at Sarajevo airport.
General Sir Michael Rose, commander of UN peacekeeping forces in Bosnia,
helped to bring about the accord, but voiced some scepticism. 'This is a
very small start to a very large problem. People should not read too much
into it as far as the overall situation in Bosnia-Hercegovina is concerned,'
he said.
A senior Bosnian army commander said he did not believe the Sarajevo truce
would work. 'I think this is yet another game which the Serbs will get away
with,' he said.
With the threat of Nato air strikes hanging over their heads, Bosnian Serbs
are due to hold talks with their Moslem and Croat foes in Geneva today to
try to bring peace to Sarajevo. The talks were originally to have dealt only
with issues such as hotlines between the factions.
Nato's jets converge with its diplomacy, Page 3
</TEXT>
<XX>
