<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 94 / Sterling falls sharply against leading currencies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sterling fell sharply yesterday against leading currencies after Tuesday's
quarter-point cut in UK base rates and against a background of political
problems for the government.
In London the pound closed at DM2.5708, more than 4 pfennigs lower than its
level before the rate cut and 2 1/2 pfennigs down on the day. It eased
further in New York to DM2.5672. Against the dollar it fell just under a
cent to Dollars 1.4605 in London, and closed at the same level in New York.
Mr Steve Hannah, chief economist at IBJ International, commenting on the
cut, said: 'This has not come across as a convincing, well-planned move.'
Many City traders complained they were unable to understand government
policy which eased rates while releasing a report indicating that inflation
could move up. The FT-SE 100 share index fell by 36.5 points before
recovering to finish 11.1 points lower at 3,429.1. UK long gilts finished
about  1/3 -point down.
Before the US and UK interest rate changes, sterling had been at recent
peaks against the dollar and D-Mark. It touched DM2.62 last month, a high
since it left the ERM in September 1992 and reached its highest level
against the dollar since October.
Markets flustered, Page 10
Government bonds, Page 31
Currencies, Page 33
London stocks, Page 42
