<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Frantic trading in Reuters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
International news and financial information group Reuters Holdings
experienced frantic trading as the company announced that it was splitting
its shares and came out with full-year results at the top end of market
expectations at Pounds 440m.
A share split, which will make the stock more marketable and liquid, had
been expected, but most analysts had anticipated a three-for-one deal at
best. When Reuters declared that investors would have four shares for every
one held, the market price moved up so fast that there were periods of
backwardation - a situation where the pace of trading leads to bid prices
being temporarily higher than the offer price. At one stage it was
technically possible to sell Reuters shares at 1980p and buy them back at
1947p.
Lehman Brothers raised its 1994 forecast by Pounds 30m to Pounds 520m,
giving 88p of earnings. Henderson Crosthwaite, the agency's broker, raised
its estimate by Pounds 20m to Pounds 520m, while BZW adjusted to Pounds 505m
from Pounds 482m. The Reuters share price leaped to a high of 2018p before
closing 60 up on balance at 1971p after heavy turnover of 2m.
</TEXT>
