FT  09 FEB 94 / International Company News: Active year for Australian
broker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
High levels of stock market activity helped McIntosh Securities, Australia's
only quoted stockbroking firm, to a ADollars 9.6m (USDollars 6.9m) profit
after tax but before abnormals. McIntosh is the product of a merger with the
Australian operations of Britain's Baring Securities.
The figure compares with a loss of ADollars 3.1m in the same period of 1992.
Operating revenues surged by 67 per cent to ADollars 58m.
McIntosh said that, on a calendar year basis, 1993 was its most profitable
trading period since 1989 - a result attributed partly to 'the buoyant
trading conditions in the securities industry,' and partly to internal
operational changes.
The wave of new issues coming to the stock market also helped push up the
results.
An abnormal profit of ADollars 12.1m from the sale of Equinet alsohelped,
leaving profits after tax and abnormals at ADollars 21.7m, compared with a
loss of ADollars 4.34m a year ago.
