<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / International Company News: Toyota plummets 48.7% to Y83bn
in six months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Toyota, Japan's largest carmaker, suffered a 48.7 per cent fall in pre-tax
profits in the six months to end-December in one of the worst business
periods in the company's history.
Pre-tax profits plunged to Y83.24bn (Dollars 764m) from Y162.34bn in the
corresponding interim period a year ago largely as a result of the weak
domestic market and the adverse impact of a sharply stronger yen.
Operating profits fell by 84 per cent to Y9.34bn - the steepest decline
suffered by the company. The ratio of operating profits to sales at 0.25 per
cent was the worst the company has experienced.
Sales fell by 13 per cent to Y3,987bn from Y4,564bn, the first decline in
turnover for seven years.
Toyota's deteriorating financial performance underlines the severity of
Japan's economic downturn, as well as the impact of the yen's sharp
appreciation against the dollar and the impact of weak demand in European
markets.
Several of Japan's leading carmakers, including Nissan and Mazda, have
suffered heavy losses following three successive years of falling new
vehicle demand in the domestic market.
Toyota, which has a calendar financial year unlike most Japanese companies
which report to March, had been able to avoid falling into loss mainly as a
result of its cost-cutting efforts, Mr Masami Iwasaki, executive
vice-chairman said.
The cost cutting efforts, which had saved Y70bn, had been more than wiped
out by foreign exchange fluctuations, which had reduced operating profits by
Y100bn. Every Y1 rise in the value of the Japanese currency against the
dollar translates into a loss for Toyota of Y10bn, it said.
While Toyota expects a moderate recovery in Japan in the second half to
June, it believes weak European demand and the adverse impact of the high
yen will continue to weigh heavily on second-half profits.
The company is forecasting pre-tax profits of Y200bn for the full year, down
from Y286.45bn previously on sales of Y8,100bn against Y10,210bn. The sales
forecast is lower than its previous forecast of Y8,700bn made in August
although the pre-tax forecast in unchanged.
</TEXT>
