<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Asian markets fail to rebound
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By OUR MARKETS STAFF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Equity markets around the world responded positively to Monday's recovery on
Wall Street, although the shock of Friday's 96-point drop in the Dow left
most of them short of recouping their losses.
In Asia and the Pacific Basin, none of Monday's big losers recovered much
ground. Hong Kong's Hang Seng index gained just 0.35 per cent after Monday's
6.1 per cent slide. Thai equities rose 1.6 per cent after a 6.8 per cent
drop, and their Malaysian counterparts by 1.3 per cent after a 4.6 per cent
downswing the day before.
In Japan, the Nikkei average, which lost only 1.4 per cent on Monday,
recovered virtually all of that ground with a 1.2 per cent improvement.
Japanese equities then showed further strength in London dealings, inspired
by the government's economic stimulus package.
Continental Europe's bourses started well, but slipped back after mild
weakness in US equities in the American mid-morning. Rate cuts were rewarded
by a new high in Belgium's Bel-20 index and, in anticipation, by an
above-average 2.2 per cent gain in Norway.
Wall Street started well but profit-taking was keeping a lid on the market
by mid-session, amid further weakness in the bond market and lingering
concern over the Federal Reserve's tightening of monetary policy.
European government bond markets failed to hold on to early gains after an
indirect signal from the German Bundesbank that it had no immediate plans to
lower German interest rates. Investors interpreted the central bank's
decision to set its 14-day repurchase agreements at an unchanged fixed rate
of 6 per cent as a sign that it was unlikely to cut interest rates before
March.
In the wake of the UK interest rate cut, other leading currencies took a
back-seat.
The dollar was slightly firmer against both the D-Mark and the Yen.
World stocks, Page 41;
Bonds, Page 33;
Currencies, Page 35.
</TEXT>
