<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Granada lifts hostile bid for LWT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
City sentiment appeared to be moving in favour of Granada Group last night
as the rental, television and leisure group increased its offer for London
Weekend Television to around Pounds 776m, or 750p a share.
Granada's final offer in the hostile takeover battle came after talks
between the two sides broke down. The new offer of 13 new Granada shares and
100p cash for every 10 LWT shares represents a near 10 per cent improvement
over the original six-for-five paper bid. The cash alternative has been
increased from 528p to 686p.
Granada shares closed 2p down at 569p yesterday, while LWT rose 35p to 737p.
Mr Gerry Robinson, Granada's chief executive, said he would have liked to
get agreement but the two sides had been 'miles apart' on price, with LWT
talking about 860p a share.
He said the increase 'recognises that people have high expectations in this
sector'. The offer would not dilute earnings in the first full year, he
added.
Sir Christopher Bland, chairman of LWT, said the revised offer was still
inadequate. He emphasised that LWT's published estimate of 1993 earnings per
share at 28.4p was 25.7 per cent higher than the figure Granada used for its
original offer. 'And yet the number of Granada shares on offer has gone up
by only 8.3 per cent. LWT shareholders will also suffer an 18.7 per cent
decrease in dividend income if they accept. What sort of increase is this?'
he asked.
The view among City analysts last night was that the Granada offer was
likely to be accepted.
Ms Katherine Pelly, media analyst at Kleinwort Benson, who last month
advocated that the Granada offer be rejected, said of the improved bid:
'It's only just there. It's hardly generous and it's still hostile.'
Privately senior LWT executives admitted yesterday the outcome would be
close but they expressed confidence that they would retain the support of
their main institutional shareholders.
The Granada offer, which represents 26.4 times LWT's estimated 1993 pre-tax
earnings of Pounds 43.8m, closes at 3pm on Friday February 25.
If LWT retains its independence it might look again at Yorkshire-Tyne Tees,
a company in which it already has a 20 per cent stake. The problem of
Yorkshire's two broadcasting licences - when LWT would only be allowed to
add one - would still have to be sorted out.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
