<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / US phone company to launch City business network
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Competition among tele-communications operators for UK business traffic is
set to intensify sharply with the launch of a network in the City of London
by US operator MFS Communications.
The news came as BT and Mercury announced the abolition of their peak-rate
calling bands, cutting between 20 and 25 per cent off prices for weekday
calls made between 9am and 1pm.
MFS is the largest competitor to the local Bell companies in the US in the
provision of telecommunications networks. The company, which had a turnover
of Dollars 108.7m (Pounds 72.4m) in 1992 and operates in 14 US cities, will
be a powerful competitor in the UK. It has a record of making swift inroads
against former monopoly telephone companies with aggressive pricing and
marketing.
MFS's City of London network, due to start in April, will be its first
outside the US. It plans extensions to other UK cities, and expects to
provide access to Paris and Frankfurt later this year.
BT's price cuts announced yesterday fulfil most of its obligation to reduce
prices before July by 7.5 per cent after allowing for inflation, under a
price cap agreement with Oftel, the telecommunications regulator.
Residential customers, who will gain little from the abolition of the peak
rate, were the main beneficiaries of a new weekend rate cutting
long-distance call prices before Christmas.
Mercury has matched BT's price cuts, and claims to be cheaper for most
long-distance calls, although discount schemes confuse the picture.
BT and Mercury will both abolish peak rates on March 9, from when a
three-minute BT local call on a weekday morning will cost 15p instead of
20p. A three-minute national call will be 10p cheaper.
Mr Michael Hepher, BT group managing director, said: 'This latest price
change not only cuts the price of calls for all our customers, but also
makes our price structure much simpler and easier to understand.'
Mercury competes with BT for long-distance and international traffic. By
contrast, MFS has built its business by competing with former local monopoly
carriers, offering access to long-distance networks.
BT is already under pressure in its local market from cable companies,
mostly US owned, building combined cable television and telephone networks.
Cable operators have more than 300,000 telephone customers and are growing
rapidly. They plan to invest more than Pounds 5bn in UK cable over the next
five years.
BT and Mercury under attack, Page 9
Observer, Page 21
</TEXT>
