<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Budget tax changes 'hit middle incomes'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour found new ammunition yesterday in its battle against the government's
taxation policy after an independent think-tank claimed that the tax rises
introduced in the last two budgets would be mainly at the expense of people
on middle incomes.
In a report published yesterday, the Institute for Fiscal Studies said the
tax rises announced last year by Mr Kenneth Clarke and his predecessor as
chancellor, Mr Norman Lamont, would largely reverse the overall reduction of
taxation in the late 1980s.
Direct taxes on incomes were reduced in the 1980s while indirect taxes,
levied on consumption, will now account for much of the revenue rise. Those
who gained from the cuts in the 1980s will not be those who lose from the
increases.
The IFS said people on middling incomes would be particularly hit by the
last two budgets because of changes to mortgage interest relief, married
couples' allowances and value added tax on fuel.
It claimed that the poorest 10 per cent of the population would have lost an
average of Pounds 3 per week from tax changes in the decade to 1995, while
the richest 10 per cent would have gained more than Pounds 30 per week.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, claimed the figures showed how the
Conservatives had turned the tax system into 'the most powerful weapon for
reinforcing inequality and creating record unfairness in British society'
and that the government had created 'the most unfair tax system since the
1930s'.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, the financial secretary to the Treasury, countered that
Tory taxation policy had boosted wealth creation, improving living standards
and increasing the amount of tax paid by high earners.
'The figures show that a man on average earnings with two children has seen
his real take-home pay grow by over Pounds 80 a week since 1979,' Mr Dorrell
told BBC radio.
The report showed that households' disposable incomes will have risen by an
average of Pounds 4 per week since 1985, but that these gains are
distributed unevenly. High-income households gained substantially from
reductions in income tax, whereas poorer households gained little and will
lose from the increases in indirect taxation.
Taxing the poor, Page 9
</TEXT>
