<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Did you know that the RAF made regular spy flights over the Soviet Union
long before America's U2 spy plane was shot down in 1960? That more than 40
'allied' aircraft were shot down and 250 aircrew lost? That 138 are still
unaccounted for, and that relatives are still trying to find out today what
happened to them? Timewatch tells the story (8.00 BBC2).
In Middlemarch the Lydgates' money worries worsen and when Tertius tries to
advertise their house for letting, Rosamond countermands his orders and
demands that they move to Bath or London. Flighty hussy. Raffles returns to
squeeze more money out of Bulstrode (you knew he would) and Ladislaw
discovers the spiteful terms of Casaubon's will (9.30 BBC2).
Walk On The Wild Side promises to report on those aspects of youth culture
that 'youth programming' tends to ignore. So instead of drink, violence and
crime on some Scottish housing estate, this will be about pony clubs and
queueing for the Proms? Er, no. This is about drink, violence and crime
among teenagers on a Glasgow housing estate (11.05 C4).
</TEXT>
