<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Oil yard problems forecast to persist
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Scottish oil platform fabrication industry faces difficulties until at
least 1996, according to Mackay Consultants, the Inverness consultancy
specialising in North Sea affairs, David Lascelles writes. One of its four
large yards - possibly two - may have to close down.
The firm estimates that capacity use was less than 20 per cent last year and
notes that employment has fallen by 5,500 in the past 18 months.
The report attributes the decline primarily to the overall decline in UK
North Sea work. Other factors include a move away from conventional steel
platforms, a lack of competitiveness and increased competition from other
fabricators.
Mackay notes that only one leading yard, UIE at Clydebank, near Glasgow, did
well in 1992-93 though its work will currently run out in May.
Of the others, Highland Fabricators at Nigg on the Cromarty Firth and
Trafalgar House at Methil, Fife, performed disappointingly, and McDermott at
Arderseir, near Inverness, disastrously.
</TEXT>
