<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / City baffled by timing and size of cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
City economists and opposition politicians at Westminster were baffled both
by the timing of yesterday's interest rate cut and by its size.
They argued that the 0.25 percentage-point cut was unlikely to have any
impact on economic recovery - and one leading City economist was concerned
that the move had coincided with new political difficulties for the
government.
Treasury ministers stressed that the cut reflected a more optimistic
assessment of inflation prospects rather than concern about the pace of
economic recovery.
Mr Michael Portillo, chief Treasury secretary, said that officials at the
Treasury and Bank of England had scrutinised a range of indicators showing
that inflation was subdued - and that this was the principal factor behind
the policy easing.
He stressed that there was no reason to doubt that the recovery in the UK
could be sustained, and he dismissed suggestions that the decision was
designed to offset the unsettling effect on world equity markets of last
Friday's 0.25 percentage-point rise in US interest rates.
'This has nothing to do with elections and tax rises,' Mr Portillo said. 'It
has everything to do with wanting to have interest rates as low as they can
be, consistent with maintaining a downward pressure on inflation.'
Opposition MPs doubted that the easing of monetary policy would improve
economic prospects.
Mr Andrew Smith, a Labour Treasury spokesman, welcomed the cut but believed
it would do little to offset tax rises, which could check the economic
recovery. He said the cut was so small that home owners might perversely
regard it as the final easing in UK monetary policy.
The Institute of Directors also said it was difficult to understand the
logic behind the UK authorities' decision. 'A  1/4 per cent cut is unlikely
to have any major impact on the economy and may be seen more as a morale
booster,' said Dr Ann Robinson, head of the IoD institute's policy unit.
'We can only assume that the chancellor of the exchequer is now developing
his strategy to offset the impact of the tax increases, which will remove
large quantities of money from people's pockets and damage the recovery.'
Mr Gavyn Davies, managing director at Goldman Sachs, the investment bank,
welcomed the easing in monetary policy. But he was disappointed that the
rate cut had occurred on the same day that the government was embarrassed by
the mysterious death of one of its backbenchers.
He said the UK authorities needed to quell the suspicion in financial
markets that the timing of recent rate cuts had been inspired by political
difficulty rather than economic reality.
Mr Graham Mackenzie, president of the Engineering Employers Federation,
said: 'We welcome the cut in rates, we would have liked more but every
little helps.'
Mr Richard Brown, deputy director-general of the British Chambers of
Commerce, said: 'I don't think a cut of 0.25 per cent will make a huge
difference to business, but it is obviously a move in the right direction.'
</TEXT>
