<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Tebbit attacks 'illegal' EU domestic subsidies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lord Tebbit last night coupled a blistering attack on law breaking and
corruption by Britain's European Union partners with a coded appeal to Tory
leaders to model the party's Euro-election manifesto on the principles in
Lady Thatcher's Bruges speech of 1988.
Speaking less than a week after another controversial attack on foreign
corruption by Mr Michael Portillo, the rightwing chief Treasury secretary,
the former Conservative party chairman hit out at 'illegal' state subsidies
provided by various EU countries for domestic industries.
Branding Rome 'the agricultural fraud capital of Europe', he described the
scale of criminal fraud linked to the Common Agricultural Policy as
'gargantuan'. He urged the government to refuse to allow any decision to be
taken at the 1996 inter-governmental conference unless the CAP was reformed.
'How can politicians have spent so much time and energy railing at the tax
on domestic heating whilst simply ignoring the vastly greater, far more
regressive food tax . . . of some Pounds 1,400 per family per year?' he
asked.
In a typically robust address to the anti-federalist Bruges Group, Lord
Tebbit mocked a 'defeatist, compromising streak' in the Conservative party
'which would disagree with most of what Margaret Thatcher (then prime
minister) said at Bruges'.
But he saved some of his harshest words for the Liberal Democrats, who are
widely expected to pose a severe threat to the Tories in a number of
Euro-constituencies, particularly in southern England.
The Liberal Democrats were 'to a person, not merely compromisers but
full-hearted articulators of the doctrine that Britain is incapable of
self-government', he said.
This view was shared by the Labour leadership, 'but not by its grass-roots
supporters'.
The former party chairman's advice to his 'friends in government' for the
European elections in June was accordingly to 'stand - and robustly at that
 -on policies which would be supported across the country, across all
classes and creeds, through all age groups and right across party lines'.
