FT  09 FEB 94 / Superstore plan dropped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
J. Sainsbury, the food retailer, yesterday dropped its plan to build a
superstore on the outskirts of Yeovil, Somerset. The scheme ran into strong
local opposition, with protestors occupying vacant buildings in the town
centre.
The decision comes less than a fortnight after Sainsbury said it would
continue with its programme of opening 20 superstores a year for the next
four years. The company denied that the withdrawal had any bearing on its
overall development programme, and said it was because Mr John Gummer,
environment secretary, had given consent for a Safeway store about a mile
away.
Sainsbury said that since it first sought a Yeovil site in 1986 'the
provision of food shopping in the town has increased dramatically'. It had
negotiated a clause with South Somerset District Council that allowed it to
withdraw if consent was given for another supermarket within five miles.
The council supported Sainsbury but opposed Safeway's scheme. After a public
inquiry Mr Gummer approved the Safeway plan in December.
Recently the Department of the Environment has taken a tougher stance on
out-of-town developments. On Monday Mr Gummer urged local authorities to
discourage them.
