<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Debate launched on radio FM slots
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Radio Authority yesterday launched a debate about what to do with new FM
frequencies which will be available from 1996 - the last likely to come to
commercial radio for the foreseeable future.
Possibilities for the 105 MHz to 108 MHz frequencies include a fourth
national commercial radio service and a new local service for all areas that
already have a local commercial station.
The authority, the regulatory body for commercial radio, suggested yesterday
that the industry's rate of growth was also an important factor to be
considered.
The authority set out four options, most mutually exclusive, for discussion:
A fourth national network that could reach more than 90 per cent of the
population.
Services similar in size and number to the present Independent Local Radio
network, including the possibility of stations switching from AM to FM
frequencies.
A new network lattice of stations classified by size, for example reaching a
radius of up to 10km (6 1/4 miles), 15km or 40km.
A combination of the services in the second and third options but
concentrated in populated areas.
