<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / NUT votes to continue boycott of schools tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's largest teachers' union yesterday decided to press ahead with its
boycott of national curriculum tests in England and Wales for another year.
The move by the NUT increases the chances of renewed political difficulties
this summer for Mr John Patten, the education secretary.
But teachers' unions are now split, as leaders of the other two unions have
opted to call off the test boy-cott.
Mr Doug McAvoy, NUT general secretary, announced the action after a poll of
members had found 89.9 per cent support for continuing the union's campaign
against the tests and the associated teacher assessments. Only 31.2 per cent
of the union's school members participated.
He said: 'The evidence of this survey is there. Teachers want time to teach.
They do not want to waste time on unnecessary and unsound statutory
assessment and testing systems.'
Tests would not take place in many schools if the NUT carries out its
threat. Both the other two unions, the NASUWT and the ATL, have agreed not
to take over the work of NUT members taking industrial action.
The two associations for head teachers have both recommended that the
boycott should be lifted, but have said they will not put pressure on
teachers who continue with industrial action.
Sir Ron Dearing, chairman of the Schools Curriculum and Assessment Authority
which sets the tests, said: 'The NUT appears not to be recognising how much
has already been done to help teachers by limiting these tests to the
essentials - national language, mathematics and science - and by finding
ways of relieving them of administrative work. My only concern is the
interests of the children.'
The Department for Education also attacked the decision. It said parents
would not understand why the NUT had not dropped the 'unnecessary' boycott
in line with the other unions.
</TEXT>
