<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Lib Dems shift focus to capture Euro seats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Liberal Democrats have refocused their European strategy to maximise
their chances of taking a number of Tory seats in the June European
elections.
The new policy, which was launched yesterday, emphasises decentralisation
and diversity instead of what one senior Liberal Democrat called 'loose talk
of a united states of Europe'.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, denied that the party was
watering down its commitment to a federal Europe but conceded that there had
been 'a change of presentation'.
The party has also gone back on its earlier pledge to reduce defence
spending by 50 per cent - which if implemented could have led to the loss of
jobs in the south-west - in light of the rise of nationalism and instability
in eastern and central Europe.
Mr Ashdown said: 'Anyone who looked around at the world in 1989 and said it
was exactly the same in 1993 would be a fool. It's not true of the
government and its not true of us.'
The Liberal Democrats, which currently have no representation in the
European Parliament, have earmarked between three and 10 of the UK's 81
seats which they believe are winnable.
The party's campaign strategy is to use the European elections to expand
throughout the south of England out of its stronghold in the south-west.
To this end the forthcoming by-election at Eastleigh - caused by the death
of Mr Stephen Milligan - could not have come at a better time for the
Liberal Democrats.
Mr Milligan held Eastleigh for the Conservatives with a majority of 17,702.
The Liberal Democrats need a swing of just more than 11.6 per cent to take
the seat, well below the 35.4 per cent achieved at nearby Christchurch.
The Liberal Democrats' new policy document on Europe, Making Europe Work For
Us, refers only to the concept of a federal Europe in terms of
decentralising power to enhance its appeal to Conservative voters in the
south of England.
It says: 'This is the vision of decentralist federalism to which the Liberal
Democrats are committed: a streamlined and effective European Union in which
power is exercised at the lowest level.'
It contrasts this with Conservative attempts 'to twist the word federal out
of all recognition, to equate with their bogey of a centralised Brussels
superstate'.
In an attempt to embarrass the government, the Liberal Democrats tabled an
early day motion noting the government's links with the European Peoples
Party, which 'works towards the realisation of a united states of Europe'.
Mr Ashdown said those who were passionate about Europe had to explain to
people, concerned about jobs and prosperity, the practical advantages of
having a pro-European policy.
'Our task is to show that Britain needs to take a lead in making Europe work
for people,' he said.
</TEXT>
