FT  09 FEB 94 / Gould expected to quit politics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Bryan Gould, a former leading member of Labour's shadow cabinet, is
expected to announce this morning that he is to quit politics.
Senior Labour officials forecast that Mr Gould was preparing to leave the
Commons after he issued a statement inviting journalists to a press
conference at Westminster today.
There was some irritation among party officials that Mr Gould had not given
advance notice to the leadership of his intentions. He is understood to have
written to Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, but the letter had not been
received late last night.
Colleagues said that Mr Gould, who quit the shadow cabinet last year in
protest at Labour's support for the Maastricht treaty, had become
increasingly disenchanted with the direction of Labour policy.
Mr Gould had some success in promoting alternative policies through the Full
Employment Forum, a pressure group for a return to traditional Keynesian
policies.
More than 30 Labour MPs joined the group, indicating a significant level of
support for his views. He was particularly anxious to combat the
conservative approach favoured by Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor,
who is one of Labour's leading modernisers.
However, Mr Gould had confided to friends that there appeared to be little
hope of influencing the party leadership before the next election.
It was not clear whether Mr Gould planned to leave the Commons immediately,
or wait until the next general election.
Party officials said they would be relaxed about a by-election in Dagenham,
where Mr Gould had a majority of 6,733 at the last election.
