<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Tribunal told of 'cover-up' on forex deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Concerns raised by a London bank officer when she was asked to destroy
suspicious foreign exchange deal notes went unheeded by management, an
industrial tribunal was told yesterday.
In 1992, Adam and Co, the Edinburgh-based private bank now owned by Royal
Bank of Scotland, announced a Pounds 21m loss from unauthorised foreign
exchange dealing.
Ms Tracey Humphreys, 30, a former assistant supervisor at the Pall Mall
branch of Adam and Co, yesterday suggested to the tribunal in Croydon, south
London, that the problems could have been discovered much earlier had
managers heeded her warnings.
Claiming unfair dismissal when she was made redundant in March 1993, she
accused Mr Richard Donaldson, the director who dismissed her, of attempting
to cover up for his own incompetence.
The bank said Ms Humphreys was made redundant because of the transfer of
foreign exchange operations to Edinburgh. She had been given a formal
warning for carrying out unauthorised money transfers from her own account
at the bank. Ms Humphreys said she made the transactions without knowing it
was against bank procedures.
Ms Humphreys, who joined Adam and Co in October 1990, said she had raised
her concerns with Mr Donaldson nearly a year before her dismissal. She had
also informed the then finance director Mr Jeremy Lowry, who has since left
the bank.
She said she was told by foreign exchange dealers to destroy deal
confirmation notes because the deals had been cancelled.
Mr Donaldson told the tribunal: 'The events of the foreign exchange had
nothing whatsoever to do with my reasons for considering Tracey Humphreys
for redundancy.'
After the hearing, he said he referred Ms Humphreys to Mr Lowry as the
appropriate person to deal with her concerns. 'It had absolutely no
relevance to her dismissal case.'
</TEXT>
