<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / Carsberg slams revised banking code
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, yesterday described
the revised code of banking practice as a wasted opportunity. The code was
published yesterday and his attack was the first of many criticisms which
came from, among others, the Consumers' Association and National Consumer
Council.
Sir Bryan said that banks and building societies had 'wasted an opportunity
to make a step increase in consumer protection'. He added that the code
'ignores major areas of consumer concern' by failing to introduce a
self-regulatory requirement to give 'best advice' to customers being offered
a range of financial services.
The code, accepted voluntarily by more than 280 banks and building
societies, is a second edition of the guidance that was issued two years ago
and imposes some fresh obligations on those who sign up to it.
These include requirements to give customers at least 14 days' advance
notice of charges and interest; not to pass customer information to other
companies in their group without the customer's express written consent, and
not to make giving this consent a condition of providing basic banking
services.
Sir Bryan was among those questioning the code's timetable, which gives
organisations until the end of 1996 to introduce pre-notification.
Mr Chris Lendrum, chairman of the working party of representatives from
banks and societies which drew up the changes, said that very complex system
changes were involved in the new arrangement, and that competitive pressures
might well contribute to earlier implementation of the change.
Some banks and societies already give customers advance notice of charges
and interest.
There was also confusion about the impact on existing customers of the new
requirement for express written consent for passing personal account details
within a bank's group of companies.
Barclays Bank, which used to make giving such consent a condition for
customers applying for new accounts, credit cards or loans, said it would
seek 'clarification' of whether and how the new code would apply where
consent had already been given in those circumstances.
Mr Maurice Healy, a member of the committee which reviewed the code and made
recommendations to the joint working party, said that the committee
envisaged that other companies in a group should not be able to use such
information until the customer had consented again.
Nor does the code resolve two issues affecting customer confidentiality on
which banks have not reached agreement with the data protection registrar.
These are 'host mailing', where an institution posts to its customers
information from another organisation, and the form of customer consent
required for passing on certain information to credit reference agencies.
Other changes in the second edition include an obligation to ensure that
customers and staff are aware of internal complaints procedures, and a
requirement to make information about the rates on interest-bearing accounts
readily available.
The new code will to come into effect in late March. The review process is
likely to start again in two years' time, with a further edition being
published in 1997.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
