<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / MPs tell board not to hinder milk plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs on the Commons agriculture committee yesterday criticised the Milk
Marketing Board for its handling of plans to open the Pounds 3.3bn milk
market in England and Wales to competition.
The committee said the board, established by statute as sole supplier of
milk from farms, did not take sufficient account of milk buyers' interests
in its original proposals to turn itself into a farmer co-operative called
Milk Marque.
'This exercise in brinkmanship has been the principal cause of the current
delay and uncertainty which the industry is undergoing,' the committee said.
Government objections that the proposals could undermine competition have
forced the board to postpone market liberalisation from until November.
The committee urged the board to treat seriously the agriculture ministry's
continuing 'hesitations' over the plan. 'One rebuff for the MMB might be
regarded as a misfortune. A second would be immensely damaging to the
industry,' it said.
When the board is abolished, farmers will be free to sell their milk either
to Milk Marque or to dairy companies.
The committee said it recognised the anxiety of the Dairy Trade Federation,
which represents distributors and processors, that Milk Marque might sign up
80 per cent of farmers. But it criticised the federation for intransigence
in its opposition to the milk board's plans.
