<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 94 / World Trade News: US cars cost 40% more in Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A new US-Japan government- sponsored study, to be published today, finds
US-made cars are sold in Japan for an average 40 per cent more than in the
US, giving Japanese cars an average 20 per cent cost advantage in their
4.3m-vehicle home market.
The study, which figures in broader talks this week over a negotiating
framework, was conducted by one US and one Japanese research company by
agreement between their two governments. Its release, at a time when the US
is demanding improved foreign access to the 4.3m Japanese car market,
clarifies the obstacles facing foreign carmakers.
According to the study, the cost of getting foreign cars approved and
adapted in Japan costs up to 5.4 per cent of the estimated transaction
price. Import, distribution, advertising, pre-delivery and construction of
repair facilities also drive up costs.
With land and building prices high, distribution is another obstacle. Only
40 per cent of Japan's dealers handle car imports along with their domestic
models, compared to 94 per cent in the US. Only 5 per cent of the dealers
handle only imports, compared with 22 per cent in the US.
Demand for US cars is hurt by the relatively low trade-in value,
particularly compared with European-made cars. The latter also have the
advantage of having made big investments in exclusive dealerships in the
early 1980s, whereas American companies used Japanese-owned dealer networks.
US car companies say they are prepared to invest in the Japanese market,
given some assurance of success.
In the clash over car trade, US officials yesterday were insisting they are
prepared to walk away from an inadequate agreement. They are insisting on
numerical goals for 'steady and significant increases' in import
penetration.
Japan's negotiators are equally insistent that they will not agree to
numerical indicators, but the numbers being put forth - 100,000 foreign car
purchases a year - have been raised by the Japanese themselves in earlier
negotiations.
US negotiators want a significant increase in the number of direct franchise
agreements between Japanese dealers and foreign vehicle makers; an increase
in North American content in parts made by Japanese companies in the US;
significant regulatory reform, deregulation and simplification of Japanese
government standards and certification; and expansion of business
relationships between US and Japanese vehicle companies.
</TEXT>
